      "header": "Health and Toxicological Information",
      "content": "Detection of moxidectin in human blood indicates recent exposure, typically through prescribed oral administration. Moxidectin is known to have a long elimination half-life, averaging between 20.2 to 35.1 days, which suggests that it remains in the system for an extended period. The primary biological systems studied in relation to moxidectin exposure include the central nervous system, where transient, mild to moderate adverse effects such as dizziness and headache have been observed. Other reported effects include eosinophilia (an increase in a type of white blood cell), pruritus (itching), and musculoskeletal pain."
